# Outstanding items — red markers (GitBook)

When writing or editing docs in this repo, mark incomplete / outstanding work so it renders **red** in GitBook.

Use `color:red` (real CSS). Do **not** use `color:$danger` — that editor token does not render via Git Sync.

## Required form

Wrap **only** the marker keyword (not the rest of the sentence or table cell):

```html
<mark style="color:red;">**TODO:**</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">**Decision needed:**</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">**TODO / Decision needed:**</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">**Review needed:**</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">Placeholder</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">Draft</mark>
<mark style="color:red;">TBD</mark>
```

### Examples

```markdown
<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<mark style="color:red;">**TODO:**</mark> Set next review date.

| Status | <mark style="color:red;">Placeholder</mark> |

<!-- ❌ BAD — bare marker -->
**TODO:** Set next review date.

<!-- ❌ BAD — wraps whole cell/sentence (breaks Markdown tables) -->
<mark style="color:red;">**TODO:** Set next review date.</mark>
| <mark style="color:red;">**TODO:** Pipeline / deals closed | Acquire |</mark>
```

## Do

- Use these markers for incomplete process, policy, SOP, assessment, and checklist content.
- Prefer `**TODO:**` / `**Decision needed:**` (bold) inside the mark for visibility.
- Re-run [`_tools/mark_outstanding.py`](../../_tools/mark_outstanding.py) after bulk edits if many bare markers remain.

## Do not

- Color ordinary prose that merely contains the word “review” (e.g. “customer review”, “Next review date” as a heading).
- Wrap trailing description text or table pipes inside the `<mark>`.
- Invent process detail to avoid a TODO — leave a red marker instead.

